B. UAV Swarm Inter/Intra-Cluster Relative Localization Modeling
After finishing clustering, the inter/intra-cluster relative localization model is constructed in this section (see from Fig. 1), and the performance is analyzed. It is known that given sufficient anchor nodes (m + 1 or more for m-D networks), the positions of the anchors in the relative map can be mapped to their absolute positions through a linear transformation [9]. It
Authorized licensed use limited to: Texas A M University. Downloaded on June 17,2025 at 19:02:29 UTC from IEEE Xplore. Restrictions apply.


11564 IEEE INTERNET OF THINGS JOURNAL, VOL. 9, NO. 13, JULY 1, 2022
is generally accepted that GSs are always far away from the drones in flight missions, leading to incomplete O-EDM acquisition and thus restricting clustering. In 3-D UAV networks, the inter/intra-relative localization method is proposed to cope with this problem.
Intercluster Localization: For all cluster BDs, four BDs, which can be connected with the GSs for communication and ranging, are selected as the ground–air beacons. These BDs are called first-level BDs (FL-BDs). FL-BDs first obtain the position based on ranging information from the GSs, then complete relative localization with other BDs called the second-level BDs (SL-BDs). Intracluster Localization: After completing relative localization among BDs, each cluster maps the absolute position of BDs to the other cluster member drones and finally completes global relative localization through data transmission.1 The inter/intra-cluster localization algorithm is introduced in Section IV-A, and suppose FL-BDs are located in cluster m∗ ∈ M. Intuitively, the amount of clusters and cluster members is the optimization variable of the proposed clustering problem, which affects the cluster localization performance through the following factors: 1) ranging packet loss; 2) cluster localization accumulative error; and 3) localization frequency. The problem is outlined as follows. 1) Ranging Packet Loss: Ranging packet loss leads to incomplete O-EDMs. First, to characterize the ranging packet loss among drones, denote the ranging signal-to-noise ratio of from UAV n to UAV k as follows:
